the media landscape. Publishers have long sought to treat news as exclusive to protect their investments against copying or "free riding." But over the centuries, arguments about the vital role of newspapers and the need for information to circulate have made it difficult to defend property rights in news. Beginning with the earliest printed news publications and ending with the Internet, Will Slauter traces these countervailing trends, offering a fresh perspective on debates about copyright and efforts to control the flow of news.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCopyrightxNews articleszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aCopyrightxNews articleszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aJournalismzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aJournalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPress lawzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aPress lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aGreat Britain.  aUnited States.  acopyright.  ahistory of journalism.  ahistory of printing and publishing.  aintellectual property.  alegal history.  amedia.  anews.  anewspapers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360772940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607729423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607729.jpg  a978-3-11-069228-0  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 